                <note rend="inline" type="source">723.2515/904: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Chargé in Peru</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Sterling</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <seg rendition="#center">[Paraphrase]</seg>
                </opener>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Lima</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1922-04-14T14:00:00-05:00">
                            <hi rend="italic">April 14, 1922—2 p.m.</hi>
                        </date>
                        <lb/>[Received 8:10 p.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>34. Your telegram no. 34, April 13, 2 p.m. I saw the President this morning, in
                    the absence of the Minister of Foreign Affairs. He explained that it had been
                    arranged that Velarde should transship at Colon for Lima, but that having missed
                    connections he had gone to New York as the quickest route to Peru. It was very
                    desirable, the President stated, that Velarde should report to Lima for
                    instructions, but in view of the Department’s feeling that any delay might
                    jeopard the success of the conference, he is cancelling Velarde’s orders.
                    Instructions would be cabled immediately, he promised, for Velarde to remain in
                    the United States. Porras will sail for New York from France on the 18th of
                    April. The counsellor to the delegation, Senor Polo, is <hi rend="italic">en
                        route</hi>, and should arrive in the United States by April 25.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Sterling</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
